                <head>335. National Security Action Memorandum No. 4<note n="0" type="source"
                        xml:id="d335fn0">Source: Department of State, <gloss target="#t_SS1"
                            >S/S</gloss>-<gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Files: Lot 72 D 316,
                            <gloss target="#t_NSAM1">NSAM</gloss> 4. Top Secret.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1961-02-04">February 4, 1961</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="to">
                    <head>TO</head>
                    <item>The Secretary of Defense</item>
                </list>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Purchases of Uranium from Foreign Countries</item>
                </list>
                <p>In the light of discussion at the National Security Council on February 1,
                        1961,<note n="1" xml:id="d335fn1">
                        <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Action No. 2398-g, taken at the 475th
                        meeting of the National Security Council on February 1, is scheduled for
                        publication in <ref target="frus1961-63v08">volume VIII</ref>
                    </note> the President requested the Secretary of Defense to consult with the
                    Atomic Energy Commission about a review of the purchases of uranium from foreign
                    countries. It is accordingly requested that this review be undertaken and that
                    this office be informed whether, in fact, there is any hope of early savings of
                    foreign exchange in this area.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BMG2">
                            <hi rend="strong">McGeorge Bundy</hi>
                        </persName>
                        <note n="2" xml:id="d335fn2">Printed from a copy that bears this typed
                            signature.12</note>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
